180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvexe"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="3"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gvexe"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Executive Branch</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="791094"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018594-20180328-025140"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="4"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gpol"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Domestic Politics</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvbod"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gvexe"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/IGV N/GEN N/PLT R/ASI R/FEO R/KN R/NME R/SK R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com FIRST STRIKE KOREA TALKS NONPROLIFERATION NORTH KOREA NUCLEAR SB126955385469309739639045841190731149704301 Donald Trump Jong, Kim Pompeo, Mike Yung-woo, Chun SYND CODES_REVIEWED Asia News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OASN </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">John Bolton Changes U.S.-North Korea Equation; Arrival of hawk on Trump team brings new factor to plans for summit with Kim Jong Un</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>SEOUL—<ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-names-john-bolton-as-new-national-security-adviser-1521758149">John Bolton's appointment</ELink> as U.S. national security adviser adds an unpredictable variable to efforts to organize a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-invites-trump-to-meet-in-north-korea-1520555014">U.S.-North Korea summit.</ELink></Para><Para>After President Donald Trump agreed this month to meet North Korean leader Kim Jong Un, Mr. Bolton, in a television interview, dismissed Pyongyang's offer of talks as a mere ploy to buy time as it develops nuclear arms.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Mr. Bolton, who has argued in favor of a <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-legal-case-for-striking-north-korea-first-1519862374">pre-emptive military strike against North Korea</ELink>, said any summit should consist of little more than planning "where U.S. cargo planes" should land to remove North Korea's weapons.</Para><Para>"If Kim Jong Un is not prepared to talk about that, it may be a very short meeting," said Mr. Bolton, a former American ambassador to the United Nations who is a Fox News analyst.</Para><Para>"Mr. Bolton may have less patience with the North, and could be less willing to give the North Koreans the benefit of the doubt during talks," said Chun Yung-woo, a former South Korean national security adviser who worked with Mr. Bolton in the 2000s.</Para><Para>That could be a good thing, Mr. Chun said. "I don't think he's a bad choice at all in dealing with North Korea at this point in time," Mr. Chun said. "If he feels North Korea is trying to buy time, he'll be able to help the North Koreans by giving them clear choices."</Para><Para>Officials in the South Korean government of <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/south-koreas-president-wants-u-s-to-ease-the-way-for-talks-with-north-1519647853">pro-engagement President Moon Jae-in</ELink> sought to highlight the advantages of having Mr. Bolton in the mix. Mr. Bolton and Mike Pompeo, newly nominated as secretary of state, have better ties to Mr. Trump than their predecessors. That could improve communication in the run-up to the meeting, the thinking goes.</Para><Para>"While serving as undersecretary of state, Bolton gained a great deal of knowledge about Korean Peninsula issues, and, most of all, he is an adviser trusted by President Trump. We will be working closely with him to resolve Korean Peninsula issues," an official from Mr. Moon's office said Friday.</Para><Para>Some political analysts and former government officials in South Korea said the appointment was likely to complicate Seoul's efforts to broker dialogue between Washington and Pyongyang.</Para><Para>By tapping Mr. Bolton and Mr. Pompeo, who also advocates a tough stance on North Korea, in quick succession, Mr. Trump has assembled a far more hawkish U.S. team than was previously in place.</Para><Para>"The philosophical gap between the more hawkish White House and the more progressive government here has widened," said Wi Sung-lac, a former South Korean diplomat who has worked on denuclearization issues. "So the importance of coordination and cooperation to make the summit a success is now even higher, and it will be difficult."</Para><Para>Conservative South Korean politicians said the selection of Messrs. Bolton and Pompeo could help ensure that Mr. Trump doesn't commit to poorly considered concessions to North Korea that could backfire later.</Para><Para>Conservative South Koreans were worried, for example, that the U.S. might agree to aid and other guarantees in exchange for a disarmament program phased in over several years—a long-term deal that the North might eventually break.</Para><Para>Mr. Bolton has a reputation as a hard-nosed negotiator dating to his 2001 appointment as the State Department's arms-control chief during the Bush administration. His image as blunt critic of disarmament efforts going back to the 1990s also prompted some South Korean officials to label him as a difficult negotiating partner.</Para><Para>In 2003 he gave a speech highly critical of North Korea's then-leader, Kim Jong Il, prompting North Korea to declare Mr. Bolton "human scum."</Para><Para>Mr. Trump has suggested the summit with the North Korean leader could take place in May. Many of the key details, such as a location, haven't been determined. North Korea hasn't publicly acknowledged the proposed meeting. Mr. Kim's initial willingness to meet with Mr. Trump was relayed orally by South Korean officials who met with the North Korean leader.</Para><Para>According to these South Korean envoys, Mr. Kim is willing to discuss denuclearization. What is unclear is what he wants in exchange.</Para><Para>The idea for a summit came in the diplomatic afterglow of North Korea's participation in the Winter Olympics in South Korea. President Moon wants to use the Olympic momentum to put the region on a path toward resolving tensions left over from the 1950-1953 Korean War.</Para><Para>However, it is an unusual setup. Normally, leaders of nations meet only after their staffs have hammered out details of an accord. In this case, Messrs. Trump and Kim would be meeting without such groundwork.</Para><Para>All the same, some conservative former officials are holding out hope.</Para><Para>"A compromise could be reached," said Mr. Chun, the former South Korean national security adviser.</Para><Para>Write to John Lyons at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:john.lyons@wsj.com">john.lyons@wsj.com</ELink> and Andrew Jeong at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:andrew.jeong@wsj.com">andrew.jeong@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-names-john-bolton-as-new-national-security-adviser-1521758149">Trump Taps Iran Hawk John Bolton for NSA Post as McMaster Departs</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bolton-trump-in-sync-on-iran-nuclear-deal-but-hold-different-views-on-russia-1521772430?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=1">Bolton, Trump In Sync on Iran Nuclear Deal But Hold Different Views on Russia</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/top-u-s-point-person-on-north-korea-to-retire-1519706309">U.S. Diplomat's Retirement Points to Administration's Divide on North Korea</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-trump-kim-summit-scrambles-the-calculus-for-key-players-1520606340">How a Donald Trump-Kim Jong Un Summit Scrambles the Calculus for Key Players</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/graphics/turnover-under-trump/">Turnover Under Trump</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By John Lyons and Andrew Jeong </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/john-bolton-changes-u-s-north-korea-equation-1521811712" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

